## Permanent PATH Fix (Not Yet Applied)

During the session, two PATH additions were made using `$env:PATH +=`, which only persists for the current PowerShell session. Once that terminal window is closed, `firebase` and `flutterfire` will stop being recognized again.

### The permanent fix (choose ONE approach):

**Option A -- Using .NET Environment API (recommended):**
```powershell
[Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable(
    "PATH",
    $env:PATH + ";C:\Users\lober\AppData\Roaming\npm;C:\Users\lober\AppData\Local\Pub\Cache\bin",
    "User"
)
```

**Option B -- Using setx:**
```powershell
setx PATH "$env:PATH;C:\Users\lober\AppData\Roaming\npm;C:\Users\lober\AppData\Local\Pub\Cache\bin"
```

> **Note:** `setx` has a 1024-character limit on the PATH value. If your PATH is already long, use Option A or manually add the two directories via **System Properties > Environment Variables > User variables > Path > Edit**.

### The two directories that need to be permanently on PATH:

| Directory | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `C:\Users\lober\AppData\Roaming\npm` | Firebase CLI (`firebase` command) |
| `C:\Users\lober\AppData\Local\Pub\Cache\bin` | FlutterFire CLI (`flutterfire` command) |

